238
25:24.660 --> 25:29.880
An orthonormal set is
simply an orthogonal set of unit vectors.

239
25:29.880 --> 25:36.210
Vectors in orthogonal
sets don't necessarily need to be unit vectors, and in fact you could
even have zero vector

240
25:36.210 --> 25:42.960
being an element of an orthogonal set, but in an orthonormal set, every vector must be a unit vector

241
25:42.960 --> 25:47.700
in addition to the
requirement that the set is an orthogonal set.

242
25:47.700 --> 25:53.880
Given what we know about the relationship between the inner product
and the Euclidean norm, we can express this
condition pretty succinctly

243
25:53.880 --> 25:57.300
as you see right here.

244
25:57.300 --> 26:07.320
And finally, an orthonormal basis is simply an orthonormal
set that forms a basis for whatever vector space
we're talking about.

245
26:07.320 --> 26:13.740
For example, if we take any
classical state set sigma and we think about the set of
all standard basis vectors,

246
26:13.740 --> 26:23.490
we see that this is an orthonormal set and in fact it's an orthonormal basis for the space of all vectors whose entries correspond to
this classical state set sigma.

247
26:23.490 --> 26:28.980
These are all unit vectors and
they're orthogonal in pairs, so it's an orthonormal set.

248
26:28.980 --> 26:34.350
and because it's a basis as well, we have that it's an orthonormal basis.

249
26:34.350 --> 26:43.470
Orthonormal sets are
always linearly independent by the way, so anytime you
have an orthonormal set, it will always be an orthonormal
basis for some subspace,

250
26:43.470 --> 26:49.650
but in this case, we have a basis for the entire space that we're working with.

251
26:49.650 --> 26:54.060
Another example is the set
containing Ket+ and Ket-.

252
26:54.060 --> 26:57.870
These two vectors are orthogonal, their inner product is equal to zero.

253
26:57.870 --> 27:09.150
and they're both unit vectors and they span the
two-dimensional space of vector corresponding to a single Qubit, so they form an orthonormal
basis for that space.

254
27:09.150 --> 27:19.650
Another example is the Bell basis, which is an orthonormal basis for the space of all
four dimensional vectors corresponding to two Qubits.

255
27:19.650 --> 27:29.070
The set containing Ket 0
and Ket+ on the other hand, is not an orthogonal set because the inner product between
these vectors is non-zero.

256
27:29.070 --> 27:38.700
They're both unit vectors and this is a basis for the vector space corresponding to a Qubit, but we don't have orthogonality.

257
27:38.700 --> 27:44.220
Here's a handy fact about orthonormal sets that we'll make use of from time to time.

258
27:44.220 --> 27:52.350
Suppose that we have some
orthonormal set of vectors, specifically, let's suppose
that we have M vectors in this set, Psi one through Psi M,

259
27:52.350 --> 28:00.960
where we're assuming that these vectors are drawn from some N
dimensional vector space, or in other words, each of
the vectors has M entries.

260
28:00.960 --> 28:07.650
As I already mentioned, orthonormal sets are always
linearly independent, so it can't be that M is larger than N,

261
28:07.650 --> 28:12.060
but it could be that M is smaller than N, and that's the case that
we're interested in.

262
28:12.060 --> 28:18.660
And what the fact states is
that if M is smaller than N, then it's always possible
to add additional vectors

263
28:18.660 --> 28:24.180
to the set we started with in order to obtain an
orthonormal basis for our space.

264
28:24.180 --> 28:33.450
To be precise, there must
necessarily exist vectors Psi M+1 up to Psi N so that the entire collection
forms an orthonormal basis.

265
28:33.450 --> 28:44.010
So you can never paint yourself
into a corner, so to speak, by somehow choosing an
orthonormal set of vectors that can't be extended to
form an orthonormal basis.

266
28:44.010 --> 28:51.360
Sometimes you can just look
at the set you start with and figure out how to extend it to form an orthonormal basis, but an alternative that always works

267
28:51.360 --> 28:58.200
is to use a procedure known as the Gram-Schmidt
orthonormalization process to construct these vectors.

268
28:58.200 --> 29:07.050
I won't explain that
procedure in this lesson or in this series because the specifics aren't
really important for us, but of course you can look
it up if you're curious.

269
29:07.050 --> 29:15.480
It's something that can
be performed by a computer in case that's relevant, so
there's no creativity involved, it's just a mechanical procedure.

270
29:15.480 --> 29:25.470
One of the reasons why this
is such a handy fact to have is concerned with a close connection that exists between orthonormal
bases and unitary matrices.

271
29:25.470 --> 29:31.620
In particular, for any square matrix U, the three conditions that you see here are always equivalent,

272
29:31.620 --> 29:35.760
meaning that they're either
all true or they're all false.

273
29:35.760 --> 29:45.660
The first condition says
that U is a unitary matrix, which means that both U dagger times U and U times U dagger are both
equal to the identity matrix.

274
29:45.660 --> 29:55.440
The second condition
says that the rows of U form an orthonormal basis
and the third condition says that the columns of U
form an orthonormal basis.

275
29:55.440 --> 29:58.560
It's actually not too hard
to see why this equivalence is true.

276
29:58.560 --> 30:07.170
Just to keep things simple, let's take a look at a
three by three matrix U as you see right here, where the entries can be any
complex numbers you like.

277
30:07.170 --> 30:13.560
Here on the left hand side I've written U conjugate transposed
just for convenience.

278
30:13.560 --> 30:22.710
If we form three vectors
from the columns of U, which here are named Psi
one, Psi two and Psi three, then if we take the
product of U dagger and U,

279
30:22.710 --> 30:30.360
you can check that each
entry of the product is given by an inner product of vectors as we see right here in this pattern.

280
30:30.360 --> 30:37.290
And now when you think about the condition that U is unitary, which is equivalent to this matrix being equal to the identity matrix,

281
30:37.290 --> 30:42.570
you see that it's equivalent
to the three vectors forming an orthonormal set.

282
30:42.570 --> 30:48.840
The diagonal entries all
have to be equal to one, so these are necessarily unit vectors, and the off diagonal
entries have to be zero,

283
30:48.840 --> 30:52.020
so it's an orthogonal set of vectors.

